result.name: Tai Woo Restaurant

reviews.text:
A cross between a old dining hall and a busy family restaurant. Went there with some friends and it was an eye opener. Busy place, good varied menu and a bustling atmosphere. There is a huge fish tank compendium in the corner with all types of creatures which I could neither recognise or describe. They where all on the menu of course. One at a time, they met there fate.
My friend was much more adventurous and eat something which had no limbs. Apart from the fact that it was not moving, it looked quite alive. He said it was excellent and that was followed by another serving of a slug like creature.
I stayed safe and tried the so and it was excellent.

Great service and yummy seafood. Prices are I. The moderate range and not too overpriced. It is a bit overcrowded when waiting for the table but the restaurant offers you snacks and drinks while you wait (a nice touch). The seafood was quite yummy and well worth what we paid.

Cantonese restaurant upstairs in Causeway Bay Plaza II. The elevator ride up or down can get a bit crowded.
Good to go with a dozen or so people to order one of their set dinners for the whole table.
The dishes are generally pretty tasty and the price decent.

Just like other ordinary Chinese restaurants, the place is a bit crowded. What worries me is the place does not look too clean to my eyes :(
Some stain or could even be some dirty from the previous meal was found on the table cloth! Waiters are too busy to take care of us, so we just cover it with some tissue paper and stay as far away from it as we could! 

Food was not as good as it was: although with very crispy skin, the chicken was too salty and the chicken itself was not juicy! It was much better before! Sweet and sour pork (Gu Loe Pork) and the steamed fish were nice!!
Great seafood at an affordable price! The small dishes, tea, and rice all cost extra, but still for the portion sizes it’s a great deal. Also really enthusiastic service!

reviews.text: I like this shopping mall. It's accessible to the nearest MTR station too.

Many restaurants for dining but not ideal for shopping
A multi-purpose building with restaurants and bars in the touristy Causeway Bay. Restaurants are predominantly Japanese, Chinese and South East Asian cuisines. Popular with locals and tourists alike.
Nice place for shopping. It's Expensive
